<br>
Congress has pretty much already given the president Carte Blanche on this issue.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>That goes back to my other question... why don't we attack EVERY country with such weapons? I mean, Pakistan has nukes, why don't we go into their country and take it away? Same with India, and China<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
This is more a matter of International agreement than anything else.  As far as why we don't attack other countries who have had them the answer is probably a bit too obvious, but I'll use the countries you've provided for specific examples.<br>
<br>
Why not Pakistan and India:<br>
  While both are quite beligerant towards each other revolving around the dispute for Kashmir, these two countries have done nothing more than pretty much any other country in the world in that they provide tacit support for the rebels in the region surreptiously and put their militaries on maneuvers, but both have relatively stable military's which don't have a habit of driving their tanks into other countries.<br>
<br>
Why not China:<br>
  Certainly China has threatened Taiwan extensively about &quot;taking them over&quot;, but considering they've been doing this for the past oh.. 40 years, I think we can assume that they don't intend to militarily take over one of the United States better allies.  China also has a particularly calculating form of leadership (Communism) so is less prone to making decisions to invade neighboring countries on a whim. (See Dictatorship)<br>
<br>
Why Iraq:<br>
  Iraq under it's current leadership hasn't exactly been the posterboy for regional stability, involving themselves in an 8 year war with Iran from 1980-1988, in which they extensively used chemical weaponry (Something they claim they don't have now btw, apparently having given it all to the DAV or some such).  After the Invasion of Kuwait and the buildup of forces on the Saudi Border, the United States took action. <br>
<br>
The key difference here is stability.<br>
<br>
It seems to me that you don't particularly care about the issues, however, you just seem to wish to push your own agenda.  <br>
