<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.vazaelle.dk">Caer Cadarn</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=siggymk5>SiggyMk5</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Led Ezra</span><br>  Posts: 2521<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(12/8/02 12:21 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm12.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=298.topic&index=22>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.in-your-ear.net/rejkid.gif  WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Will you vote to re-elect George W. Bush?</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Quote:<br>
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
Now, I am not against going to war Iraq per se, I just want it done legally. We must have a reason, not speculation, and it has to be declared by Congress, not the President. <br>
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
Congress has pretty much already given the president Carte Blanche on this issue.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Tragically so.  Pres. Bush can legally, from the point of view of American politics, engage in conflict with Iraq.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>As far as why we don't attack other countries who have had them the answer is probably a bit too obvious, but I'll use the countries you've provided for specific examples.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Ooh... this should be fun...<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Why not Pakistan and India:<br>
While both are quite beligerant towards each other revolving around the dispute for Kashmir, these two countries have done nothing more than pretty much any other country in the world in that they provide tacit support for the rebels in the region surreptiously and put their militaries on maneuvers, but both have relatively stable military's which don't have a habit of driving their tanks into other countries.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Well, actually, India is stable and mostly capitalistic democracy, so really our kinda people.  Not to mention the economic ties between the US and the world's second most populous country are extensive.  Really, other than the Kashmir conflict, India's a pretty decent place by American standards.  Of course, they have nukes, and we don't like anyone but us having nukes, but we get along so it's mostly okay.<br>
<br>
Pakistan, on the other hand, is a completely different issue.  They used to be a relatively moderate and democratic Islamic state.  Of course, certain aspects of the government funded the Taliban regime in Afghanistan.  Since we couldn't have cared less about Afghanis or Pakistan's ties to their oppression during that period of history, it wasn't an issue.  Then, in a military coup Musharraf ousts the democratic institutions in Pakistan and places the country under his military rule.  Under him, conflicts in Kashmir increase and Pakistan detonates a nuclear weapon.  And his grip on power in tenuous, he, too, could get ousted and possibly replaced by a hard-line fundamentalist.  Let's see... loose cannon military leader known to have nuclear weapons and constantly at odds with a nation we're quite friendly with... who also has nuclear weapons.  You'd think Pakistan... or at least Musharraf, would be at the top of our list of &quot;things to take care of.&quot;  But no, we need to use his soil for our retalitory strike into Afghanistan following 9/11.  So suddenly Musharraf is a good guy.  Gosh... if only Castro had let us put nuclear weapons in Cuba rather than Russia...<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Why not China:<br>
Certainly China has threatened Taiwan extensively about &quot;taking them over&quot;, but considering they've been doing this for the past oh.. 40 years, I think we can assume that they don't intend to militarily take over one of the United States better allies. China also has a particularly calculating form of leadership (Communism) so is less prone to making decisions to invade neighboring countries on a whim. (See Dictatorship)<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
China's brand of Communism is actually not very close to Dictatorship.  It's really more of an Oligarchy with a small amount of Meritocracy supporting a partially Marxist system.  Nonetheless, it is particularly calculating and not prone to making invasion decisions on a whim, but most countries ruled by commitee are that way, the US included (or at least, until Bush got his Carte Blanche).<br>
<br>
But otherwise... hmm... we've gone to war with China in the not too distant past (see: Korea).  They are Communist, and Americans institutionally hate Commies.  We bombed their embassy (accidentally).  They held our planes and air crews hostage.  The threat to Taiwan is real if not entirely probable.  They have nukes.  They're continuously throwing their considerable weight around more in global politics and they're a sleeping bear of economic power which is waking up, and none too slowly.  They're even trying to put someone on the moon!  Really, these guys are huge threat.<br>
<br>
Oh, but we have huge economic ties to them... and they have a huge army.  Sure, if we went to war we could kick their ass at sea and in the air... and their nuke delivery systems aren't the world's greatest.  But if we had to fight China on the ground... in China.  That would be a bloody mess, and any nukeless victory would be very costly in American lives.  And a nuke victory.  Well aside from making us the world's biggest pariahs and killing millions of innocent civilians... well aside from that it wouldn't be too bad... assuming they had trouble getting a nuke to our shores...<br>
<br>
Really, the better investment is to work with 'em.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><br>
Why Iraq:<br>
Iraq under it's current leadership hasn't exactly been the posterboy for regional stability, involving themselves in an 8 year war with Iran from 1980-1988, in which they extensively used chemical weaponry (Something they claim they don't have now btw, apparently having given it all to the DAV or some such). After the Invasion of Kuwait and the buildup of forces on the Saudi Border, the United States took action. <br>
<br>
The key difference here is stability.<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Odd that you should mention the Iran-Iraq war.  That was our war.  We used Iraq as a proxy force.  History is pretty clear on that.  The US was concerned about one regional power in that area growing too powerful, so by setting Iran and Iraq at the each other's throats and giving them the materials to make it a long, bloody and ultimately inconclusive war, we could keep things balanced (oh, and our real allies, Israel and Turkey, could get some breathing room).  And yes, they used chemical weapons.  American and Russian ones.<br>
<br>
This was our war.  And, from our point of view, it went splendidly and accomplished all its goals.  It made the region more stable... at least insofar as it led to the type of stability we wanted.  Saddam even led one of the least fundamentalist nations in the area.  Saddam was perfect.<br>
<br>
But Iraq continued to build its military might after the war ended.<br>
<br>
Then came Kuwait.  Iraq had long wanted Kuwait after the Brits (mostly) divided up the Ottoman Empire following the first World War.  Iraq finally had the means to do so decisively.  They put out diplomatic feelers and after not getting a hugely negative response, went for it.  But there was a problem.  Oil was involved.  Other nations started getting pissed off, especially because Iraq doesn't manage its oil fields in the same globalization friendly way that Kuwait did.  Saudi and Iraqi forces simultaneously built up at the border... among other things, the Saudis knew the storm that was coming (pun not intended).<br>
<br>
Remember, the Cold War had just ended and there were a lot of US and NATO forces, formerly tied up in Eastern Europe, which now either had to be used, moved, or decommisioned.  It seemed like an invasion of Iraq would be a reasonable use, so they were committed.  Had the Cold War still been occuring and Saddam not subsequently decided to otherwise flex his military might, he might have gotten away with it.<br>
<br>
So the world got together and kicked Iraq's ass and returned Kuwait to the Kuwaitis.<br>
<br>
Since then, in realm of regional instability Saddam has... well he's pretty much done nothing.  He's kicked some UN inspectors out, but how that ties to regional stability I have no clue.  Iraq's been tied, in very circouitous 7-degrees fashion, to international terrorism.  Maybe.  Saddam put out a hit on former President Bush.  Still, not much threat to regional stability.<br>
<br>
But wait, hold the press...  that was the current President's dad... there's a whole lot of oil involved... Americans still hate Saddam because, hey, he's our traditional enemy now that the USSR is gone... there's a War of Terror which a conflict with Iraq could kinda sorta be tied in to...<br>
<br>
Now, I was obviously making fun in that last paragraph.  There are some reasons to go to war with Iraq.  Some hold more water than others.  However, regional stability is not one of them.  Starting a war, especially with a wholly expeditionary force, is never good for regional stability.  A war there could lead to further splintering of Iraq, renewed Kurdish unrest in Turkey and Iran and the distributing of whatever weapons of mass destruction Saddam's regime has to whomever can find and loot the sites first.<br>
<br>
A war with Iraq would not be about stability.<br>
<br>
--Siggy <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=truthreason>TruthReason</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>I'm actually Goanad.</span><br>  Posts: 293<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(12/13/02 2:42 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm12.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=298.topic&index=23>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Will you vote to re-elect George W. Bush?</span><hr size=1> If people would have not voted for that kook, Ralph Nader, we would not have to muck through mess after mess created by Dubya, our first Supreme Court appointed President.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=wodahsthemad>Wodahs the Mad</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Lurker</span><br>  Posts: 2<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(1/12/03 6:52 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm12.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=298.topic&index=24>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Will you vote to re-elect George W. Bush?</span><hr size=1> HELL NO! Bush is a moron, and is not fit to run any type of government at all. That stupid bastard is going to kill us all with his stupid stupidness (sorry i know its not a word...couldnt think of anything else). <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=tryunn>Tryunn</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.spazzmania.com/Ohtrux/A.jpg" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Contributing Member</span><br>  Posts: 25